http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Theatre Curriculum Standards for grades 6-8.
Script Writing - Students will write scripts through improvising, drafting, and refining scripts based on personal experience and heritage, imagination, literature, and history.
Understand the principles of basic scene writing.
Explore dramatic situations within script.
Develop scripted scenes through individual or collective experiences.
Understand language and structure of script.
Participate in script writing by structuring scenes based on improvisation.
Identify character within script.
Character Acting - Students will develop basic acting skills by portraying characters in improvised and scripted scenes.
Use imagination to create character.
Develop characters through facial expressions, body language, and voice.
Create characters based on a given situation.
Explore physical and emotional depths of characters.
Employ improvisational skills using appropriate guidelines to develop a character.
Implement movement and vocal techniques to express character traits.
Scene Design - Students will design by developing environments for improvised and scripted scenes.
Explore technical elements such as lighting and set design.
Identify costume, set, props, lighting, sound, and make-up for an improvised or scripted scene.
Understand safety issues within technical theatre.
Construct elements of a set following appropriate safety procedures.
Identify roles of technical theatre personnel.
Directing - Students will direct by organizing rehearsals for improvised and scripted scenes.
Explore responsibilities of the director.
Develop leadership and collaborative skills through directing improvised and scripted scenes.
Construct a rehearsal schedule.
Understand basic script analysis.
Understand technical elements (e.g., costume, lighting, sound) for improvised or scripted scenes.
Research - Students will research by using cultural and historical information to support improvised and scripted scenes.
Explore and discover contributions of people in various cultures for appropriate use in improvised and scripted scenes.
Examine historical information to support improvised and scripted scenes.

Theatrical Presentation - The students will compare and incorporate art forms by analyzing methods of presentation and audience response for theatre, dramatic media (such as film, television, and electronic media), and other art forms.
Recognize how dance, visual art, and music are used in theatre.
Understand the role of the audience and demonstrate appropriate etiquette.
Scene Comprehensions - Students will analyze, evaluate, and construct meanings from improvised and scripted scenes and from theatre, film, television, and electronic media productions.
Analyze and respond to a variety of theatrical experiences.
Analyze the theme of scenes from theatre, film, television, and/or electronic media productions.
Context - Students will understand context by analyzing the role of theatre, film, television, and electronic media in the community and in other cultures.
Recognize the historical impact of theatre, film, television, and/or electronic media on society.
Understand the relationship between theatre and society.
